According to the 2018 Sustainability Report, "We currently rely on the outcomes of second-party audits [such as the Responsible Business Alliance, and suppliers] and limited risk screenings to evaluate child labor risk in our own operations. We have yet to implement a process for the evaluation of suppliers."
Some auditing is therefore not undertaken, but not by the Company themselves and not against the Company's
own code of conduct.

According to the 2018 Sustainability Report, "We’ve not yet developed a strategic approach to responsible
shipping materials management, although some of our facilities have implemented material efficiency projects"
As of 2018 it is understood that no targets were in place for packaging efficiency, although cardboard quantities
were partially being tracked.

According to the Company website "We don’t actively manage water use, but many of the buildings we occupy
are equipped with water-saving devices. We participated in CDP’s supply chain water security reporting process.
Our 2018 CDP water score was C (Awareness), aligning with sector and regional averages. An awareness of the
issue therefore exists within the Company, however evidence of progressive improvement in efficiency was
not identified.

According to the 2018 Sustainability Report, "Our environmental stewardship policy outlines numerous strategies for the minimization of waste at our facilities. Sites with environmental management system certifications may adopt targets that exceed the corporate minimum reduction of 5 percent per year. " Further detail on data and targets is given in the report and waste is understood to be a key focus area for the CSR team.

According to the Company website "Water isn’t a material issue for us based on our latest materiality assessment, but we expect that water scarcity in some regions will eventually have an impact on our upstream supply chain. " An awareness of the issue therefore exists within the Company, however evidence of a carbon reduction policy or management system was not identified.

Various energy data and metrics are given on the Company website and within the annual sustainability report. Furthermore, an annual submission is made to the CDP, detailing energy management and resulting emissions.
The Company publishes CDP responses on its website, including CDP Supply Chain Climate Change which includes detailed GHG emissions data.
The composition of governance bodies is stated within the annual sustainability report (board of directors comprised 5 men and 1 woman as of 2018).

According to the 2018 Sustainability Report, "Learning and development (L&D) is a corporate function at Ingram
Micro. We continue to consult a cohort of L&D professionals to facilitate best practices and approaches to learning, but each country has its own approach based on needs and resources. We’ve developed and maintain administrative policies for our online learning management system and make all tools available to our countries of operation. For our leadership development track, our corporate L&D team works with our global leadership team to identify individuals for the program". "We evaluate total and per capita training hours, regional participation, overall participation rates and participation by gender in tuition reimbursement programs, and the rate of performance reviews. "
According to the 2018 Sustainability Report, some sites hold environmental management system certifications, although this is not mandated at a group level.

According to the 2018 Sustainability Report, in 2018, "we promoted entrepreneurship, innovation and creativity Through the international Comet Competition in partnership with MassChallenge. The competition awards USD 5,000,000 in funding to 60 independent start-up software vendors across five continents". Furthermore, the Company is a member of the Association for innovation, business excellence, services and technology (AIBEST).

According to the 2018 Sustainability Report, during 2018 "we solidified plans to launch a pilot program with an industry leading provider of supplier sustainability assessments by mid-2019 and set a target to assess 100 key suppliers by year-end 2019. " The intention was to use the outcome of this initial assessment to shape the management approach going forward however it is not clear if this has subsequently happened or what form it has taken. Furthermore, while all suppliers are required to adhere to applicable laws and regulations in the standard supplier agreement, no broadly applicable
requirements for social and environmental conduct beyond compliance are mandated.

According to the 2018 Sustainability Report, there is no board level oversight of the CSR program and no dedicated executive role, "but we evaluate the structure and effectiveness of our CSR organization annually. The senior CSR manager provides periodic program updates to a seven-member, cross-functional executive leadership committee".
